The worst omakase I've ever been to. Slow service with a sever with an attitude.
We ordered Yazawa Omakase and it took over 50 minutes JUST FOR THE APPITIZERS AND 9 PIECES OF MEAT that we're supposed to grill on our own, even though the store was not busy. The table behind us were served way faster with the same server.
Also ordered garlic rice and asked for spoons, and some random sauce was on the spoons. We complained to the server a couple of times and asked for the manager(was off) and the server's attitude was what made our experience worse. We lost our appetite and asked for the bill without getting the last portion of the omakase because of her attitude.
What kind of omakase takes that long especially when it comes raw and you cook it for yourself?
I didn't expect such service at a pricey restaurant that I wouldn't even get at McDonald's. Shout out to the female japanese server that ruined our night :)!

<user>105750821251983801457<//user><username>Charlie Walls</username>< Time>
1542139989922< /Time>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
The wagyu appetizer simply melted in your mouth, I particularly loved the tartar. Each and every meat had a intense marbling and a distinct and memorable flavor. It was definitely a splurge, but well worth it! There's like 5 different kinds of omakase: 100, 120, 140, 160, and 180. The minimum of $100 has 3 raw beef appetizers and 5 different of cuts (4 pieces of beef tongue and skirt steak, then it's just 2 slices of each meat after that because the quality gets better!) The more expensive omakases have uni. Omakase doesn't come with any sides so I got the Yazawa salad (light and refreshing!) and garlic rice with wagyu beef in clay pot.
PARKING: street metered, but you know how that is around Rodeo Dr...so just make your life easier and park in the parking stalls behind the yazawa building.<//Text>

This place is more about tasting than eating. They sell a special experience and they deliver. We had the chef's choice and I think this is the best meat I ever had. The service is on spot as well: our waiter stayed at our table and prepared the different pieces of wagyu right in front of us (you can also do that yourself if you think you know better). Definitely come here if you're into really good beef - it's worth the (admittedly hefty) price.< /text>

<review>Allow me to preface this review by stating that I know Japanese meat. I grew up partially in Japan and have traveled throughout the country extensively. I‚Äôve eaten yakiniku more times than I could count. My meal at Yazawa was an absolute disaster.

I was in LA for a few days for a show and decided to seek out yakiniku, as there aren‚Äôt too many places outside of Japan where you can get Japanese beef. A quick Yelp search revealed that my relatively-nearby options were Yazawa and Manpuku. It looked like Manpuku only served US ‚Äúwagyu‚Äù, so I opted for Yazawa, as my entire quest originated from the desire to have Japanese beef.

While Yazawa did serve Japanese A4/A5 wagyu (and the meat itself was good), the chef/restaurant/owners absolutely destroyed the meat with sickening amounts of non-optional sauce (the meat - ALL cuts of the wagyu - arrived pre-soaked in the stuff). The omakase began with a 3-dish appetizer, and from the very first bite, I knew I was doomed. The tartare may as well have been tofu or ground beef from Ralph‚Äôs, because you literally could taste nothing but their nauseatingly sweet sauce - 2 out of 3 appetizer dishes were just hosed down with this stuff - they were indiscernible. An initial bite sets the tone of the meal, but whatever, maybe things would improve.

No, no they would not. The first pieces of meat were inexplicably USDA cuts. Nothing special, but not offensive, either. These unremarkable pieces were salted and peppered with no sauce, which is absolutely ridiculous - they overpower the prized wagyu with sauce, yet serve the cheap USDA cuts with an understated salt and pepper, when it‚Äôs brutally obvious that this should be the inverse. Then came our $200 meager platter of Japanese wagyu for two. And it was positively DRENCHED in Yazawa‚Äôs Signature Sauce (TM). My partner and I each tried a single bite to give it a chance, and it was terrible. All we could taste was sugar, ginger, and garlic. The sauce was cloying, the meat was woefully undersalted (and quite literally untasteable), and the experience was just depressing. Wanting to salvage something out of this meal, we asked our server to explain this saucing decision and ask if we could perhaps replace the remainder of our meat with pieces that were simply salted and peppered. We were offered nothing more than a trite, bored response of ‚Äúthat‚Äôs how the omakase comes‚Äù. We were never informed, via the menu or the server, that our meat would be sauced to oblivion, and never even given the option to opt for salt instead.

We explained that we are well-versed in yakiniku, and the meat was being ruined by this sauce (which we were never informed of), and Yazawa absolutely REFUSED to do anything about it - they wouldn‚Äôt replace our meat, offer us supplemental cuts, NOTHING. I honestly wished I had just walked out, but I stoically choked down the maple-syrup-coated meat and got the $300 check, whereupon they couldn‚Äôt be bothered to do so much as remove our drinks from the bill, when we clearly had a horrific experience. They were so unapologetic, it was remarkable.

Considering the price and my expectations, this may have been the worst dining experience of my entire life. Only dine here if you like the idea of a business that takes exquisite, difficult-to-acquire Japanese beef and absolutely saturates it in a foul, saccharine sugar-garlic-ginger-shoyu glaze, COMPLETELY obliterating and masking the flavor of the prized meat itself, and then selling it to rich people with no taste or palate, from a Rodeo Drive storefront. Oh, yeah, and they also soak the appetizers in the sauce. They must have buckets of the stuff in the kitchen and apply it to everything in sight with a fire hose.

Between the food and service, for what they charge and promise, this was a legitimate 0/5 for me.</review><time>1557348893083</time>< Gmap_id>

<user_id>111001598936262105015<//user_id><Rating>5</Rating><Text>So AMAZING. One of the best restaurants, and definitely the best yakiniku I've been to thus far.

Yazawa is a meat company that happens to have restaurants around the world, 12 to be exact and this location being the only one in the states. All their Wagyu beef are flown overnight from Japan and never frozen. Our server suggested to get the Omakase, but my bf and I decided to get everything a la carte as we wanted specific dishes.

Wagyu Tartar w/ Egg Yolk (3/5) - a little tough, flavoring was good but on the sweeter side. Meat didn't taste as fresh as the rest.

Assorted Kimchi (2/5) - comes with Chinese Cabbage, Radish, and Mountain Potato. It was alright, nothing special.

Yazawa-Yaki (4/5) - this is wagyu sirloin, the meat was marinated in a sweet bbq sauce and not as soft as the Zabuton, as expected, but nonetheless amazing with the egg wash. I liked that they whipped the egg yolk. This comes as a per piece order. I loved it, but my bf was not a fan.

Zabuton (5/5) - the most marbled wagyu beef on the menu. It literally melts in your mouth. I died and went to heaven when I took the first bite. Comes in 4 thin square pieces, enough for 2 people to try. Highly recommend!!

Beef Tongue (5/5) - best tongue I've ever had! Thick fresh cuts. It's 100x better than Anjin and Gyutan. It was so tender and juicy. I would recommend asking for lemon on the side and not dipping it in any sauce. Just squeeze some lemon juice on top and enjoy. Highly recommend ordering. Would come back just for this.

Garlic Japanese Wagyu Rice (5/5) - amazing wet fried rice served in a claypot which makes the rice a little crispy, my favorite. If you love garlic, I would recommend asking for extra garlic. The flavoring of the fried rice was mesmerizing. My bf was in love with this dish. Must order!!

Overall, I would highly recommend trying this place if you have the chance to. You will not be disappointed by the quality of this place. Meat quality is exceptional and I cannot wait to come back to try their omakase and other dishes. Service is a little slow, but they were nice. Place is pretty clean.<//Text></record></dataset><record>

< Review>
There‚Äôs nothing like that feeling of being promptly greeted and whisked right to your table reservation. Ahh, let‚Äôs get to business! Shall we have the omakase style or a la carte? The wagyu truffle uni pairing is hard to pass up! Our a la carte plates start to roll in, love the table gestures and plate presentation - it truly must be all in the wrist! Then our mains arrive and wow, the staff‚Äôs agility is quite impressive! We‚Äôre about 36 minutes in at this point and finished most our plates and being force fed sake faster then freshmen and their 1st keg stand. We finish our soup, ahh here comes the desert menu! Nope, the bill arrived, not even a fortune cookie. One hour in and $500. I could only imagine omakase would have been like carnival ride where staff use a nerf gun to unload 7 wads of wagyu mash in your mouth from across the room. < Review>
This car wash is just the worst, HEED WARNING, STAY FAR AWAY FROM THIS PLACE AS POSSIBLE!... First off everyone is just sitting down as you drive up, on top of the fact that they are already usually understaffed. Service is mediocre. The guys do a lousy job of vacuuming the vehicle for approximately 2 minutes before they run it through the machine. BEWARE as they may forget to close your doors before washing it. FYI, My car is brand new. The guy forgot to close my rear door and my car interior got soaked in the process. I didn't find out until they honked for me that it was ready. I inspect the vehicle as I usually do. The guys there expect a tip for there mediocre service and give you dirty looks if you don't tip. I noticed my car was soaked so clearly I didn't tip. I asked to speak to a manger, and was walked over to some guy that did not apologize for the damages, he simply said ok we'll take care of it. I still requested to speak to a manager, they said I would have to come back because there was nobody I could speak to. No type of remorse or customer service on this business' part. They did not offer to comp me or refund me for the terrible service and damages I received. I was so upset with this place and definitely will not be going back.</Review>

Funny people say the receptionists were bad but they were about the best thing I saw or had the pleasure of talking with.

To preface this review by saying I have 3 years of nursing school and 6 years of LPN nursing experience.

I had an Appointment with PA Philip Ford and it wasn't very positive. In fact I would feel better if PA Ford changed his first name to "Ford" and his last name to "Truck", because that is exactly what he is.....A "TRUCK".

Why? Well first of all he told me that my problem isn't really his specialty. That's fine, and I understand that. Dr. Truck gave me another perscription of what I currently had and some positive effects during the trial. That's fine. Dr. Truck sent the perscription to the wrong pharmacy and I had to wait an hour in the parking lot with a 102 temperature.

It's been 6 days and it isn't working. Fever is gone but pain and swelling still a go, so I made it a point to call 3 more times and had to keep calling to get him to change the perscription.

I researched Google for my particular problem and it specifically suggested 4 medications. 3 of them I've already tried during my nightmare 4 months of having this infection so I was hoping for the strongest one Google recommended. I also inquired with my other Doctor friends back home and they agreed that I should try the stronger one.

Well when I called the last time Dr. Truck said he would send the perscription in. Well I went to the pharmacy today and guess what was there? NOTHING, Dr. Truck didn't send my perscription to the right CVS eventhough he mirrored the words out of my mouth as I was saying the correct address. This was the second time he sent my drugs to the wrong pharmacy.

Well it's back to playing phone tag and I had to call back again with no response. So I decided to call again before they closed. The receptionist said that, "Dr. Truck,  changed my perscription twice and he's not going to change it anymore!" WTF?

First of all you changed it once, today when you sent it to the wrong pharmacy. Second, you sent an antibiotic that I was on last month and didn't work at all. I guess you would have known that if you actually looked at my chart. Third, if you would just look in your PDR you could have suggested the right medication in the beginning but you're too much of an amateur to care.

Thank you Dr. Truck for nothing! He also said I should just wait to see my specialist which All-Med hasn't sent the paperwork to Sutter for yet. It's nice sitting here in pain for someone else's incompetance.

Well I better focus on my specialist because Dr. Truck sucks. So when I called Sutter the receptionist said she didn't receive the paperwork yet. How funny, I received the paperwork at my house but the specialist hasn't received anything.

I would like Dr. Truck (AKA PA Ford) to call me personally and apologize for being un-caring and inept at his duties.</Review>

<Text>Came to this place because I was invited. How ever this is like the saying of don't judge a book by its cover. From the outside it doesn't look so great. But once you open the doors and walk in it's an entirely different world. This place is very clean, Art Deco is rustic and very ranch like. The servers were very easy going but enthusiastic at the same time (Great service from their part). The food was something that I did not expect.  We got some shrimp cucarachas (roaches) and the way these thing are prepared is just an exciting party of flavor ready to explode in your mouth. They were delicious. Also tried the carne asada plate, comes with a side of rice, beans, and a small salad. The beef itself was very very flavorful and juicy. We also had a michelada and even this thing come with an excellent presentation that will not only enchant your eyes but leave your taste buds wanting more.
Over all the food Is definitely something I would expect from a high end restaurant that might be overlooking the beach out somewhere expensive. But it's not. It's in our neighborhood and it's definitely a jewel in itself. I would recommend you go try this place.<//Text><pics>None</pics>< response>
None< /response>

<Review>This is a very nice airport. I don't fly frequently, so I cannot compare amenities with other airports very well.
What I can say is that the people working here, as well as fellow travelers were positive and helpful.

<Rate>5<//Rate>< Review>
It's been almost two years since we last traveled and to say I was nervous was an understatement. However,  SJC took a lot of safety precautions that helped alleviate my worries,  especially when traveling with my twin toddlers who are not currently vaccinated.  Mask are required and they ask that everyone maintains socially distant from one another.  In the security line,  they have plexiglass dividing security from travelers.  In the bathroom,  they've added dividers between each sink to ensure a more individualized space.  Chairs has sign to ensure that ppl are seated away from one another.  Security and employees at the airport were very friendly and helpful,  especially since we were traveling with a double stroller and toddlers who got confused with all that was happening around them.  We had a great experience at SJC, but then again,  we've airways had a positive experience here.  It's great to see the airport continue to expand and improve in the last two decade.< /Review>

<rate>5<//rate><Review>Going through TSA Pre was a little different from before the pandemic. You have to wear a mask, show your ID, not your boarding pass, and when they have your information on screen, they ask that you pull down your mask so they can make sure it is you.

For Southwest, there is a watering station to fill up your bottle on the left. This airport is easy to get to and very convenient.
It is a very friendly airport. You may ask anyone with questions or help.

Their Lost and Found office is amazing! I had left my laptop in a bin at TSA security check and they called me the next day that it was found and turned in.
I was instructed to fill out a from on the day I found out my laptop was missing. The form was online and was so easy to fill out and submit.

This airport is very organized especially for Uber.
I got picked by Uber easily and conveniently.

I recommend to everyone when you can to fly San Jose Airport.</Review>

< Text>
Small but friendly airport. It's covid times and likely more open otherwise, but I still managed to find mediocre food,  drinks to go only, and friendly service on my layover. Bathrooms clean. Security looked short and simple. Long lines anywhere with decent food. Crazy how friendly everyone was to me, they were amazingly nice. Ten minutes after my earliest boarding time started they called my name over the loud speaker to come to the flight, there were five others and they warned us each by our full names of the pending take off over the loud speaker with 20 minutes to spare. Clearly everyone working here is focused on helping passengers have a successful and comfortable travel experience- much appreciated!! Great airport, but very small. I bet late or early there's nothing open so be prepared for that, but you'll find everything you need right here.< /Text>

<Name>Bob Atkin< /Name>< Resp>

< user_id>
108891609715473721271< /user_id>
<date>1571813952752<//date>< Review>
San Jose's airport is a great option if you're in the bay area. It's a little out of the way if you're heading to San Francisco or Oakland, but it is a lot less hectic and the terminal is in great shape.

I'm just traveling through, but I did have to get my bags from baggage claim and I will need to check them back in tomorrow morning (no connecting flight this evening.

Baggage claim consists of just two carousels so it's not too difficult to find which one is spewing forth luggage from your flight.

Check in is on the same level. Most of the food , drink, etc. vendors are in the terminal area that is past security, but there is a Starbucks and a little "marketplace" available by baggage claim if you need something when you're getting your bags.

Not sure about parking, but there appears to be a huge garage structure right across the street.

There is a sign for a USO, but all I could find was the Military Lounge, which is not a USO and is only for active duty military personnel. It's something the airport does for the military and is a nice thing.< /Review>
< Rating>
4<//Rating>

<Review>Back in the day... That is before Corona virus took over... When I had to do a lot of day trip traveling down to southern California, this airport was ideal. I could park in a parking lot that was literally butted up against the terminal and I could go from my car to the TSA line in under 3 minutes. Getting in and out was a fair breeze. The interior of the terminal could use some work geometrically I mean. It's one long line of gates on one side and shops on the other. <Rate>5< /Rate>< Text>
In our experience, this airport has been infinitely more pleasant than SFO. If there is any way that we can possibly travel via SJC instead of SFO, we do so. Overall, we find SJC cleaner, more convenient and friendlier.

Many of the negative reviews seem to concern the TSA personnel. I think it's important we understand that they are not well compensated and much is asked of them in return, with many passengers not paying them the courtesy they deserve. If we all make an effort to be courteous, we will receive more courtesy in return.

It also speaks well of SJC that negative reviews here are conscientiously responded to, typically with offers to contact appropriate parties, to follow up on issues that deserve attention.

TIP: We ourselves did experience some issues relating to our unfamiliarity with the layout and the parking system. I would highly encourage anyone using this airport for the first time to make an effort to check things out online before their trip -- and always arrive earlier, to allow for possible missteps.

As Roy Rogers used to sing, "Happy trails to you!"</Text>

<rating>4<//rating><Text>It's all about the gates - and in this case, the gate structure is pretty good. Plenty of security lanes, efficient TSAPre, and the traffic through the gates tends to be low enough that you usually get through in 5.minutes or less (way less, with TSAPre).

Inside, there really isn't much in the way of amenities - just the usual assortments of Peets, Starbucks, chain restaurants, etc.

<UserId.>117969747549437587005</UserId.><name>Yan Kuang</name><date>1581618684027<//date><rate>4< /rate>< Text>
There are many areas to talk about when it comes to an airport. From the design to the operations, and to the amenities within. So instead of bore you with the details, here are a few useful bullets.
- Small airport, but everything is reachable within a small distance.
- Connected terminals so accessing different amenities are possible.
- Fast Internet (most of the time).
- Very decent lounges if you have access. (occasional restrictions).
- Lower flight cadence when compared to bigger airports like SFO.
- Less airline options when compared to bigger airports like SFO.</Text>

<user>116787012649916667934<//user><Name>noodlenoggin<//Name><Date>1595443438162</Date><rate>5</rate>< Text>
I've had a couple of long-term projects in the Bay Area, and my airport of choice is SJC.  San Francisco may have better dining and shopping, but SJC is 100% better at being on-time with their core business of airplanes landing and taking off.  Served by the major airlines, and a huge Southwest hub, if you fly Southwest, there are nearly as many tickets to SJC as to the larger SFO.  Plus, the terminal is super-easy to navigate -- it's just one long concourse -- you can walk inside security from the end of Terminal A, all the way through Terminal B.  Plus, the rental car center is just across the road from Terminal B.  Consistently, I'm able to return my rental car, walk across the road, get through Terminal B security (Pre Check), and walk the length of the airport to my flight in Terminal A...all in far less than a half-hour.<//Text>

< review>
It's all about the gates - and in this case, the gate structure is pretty good. Plenty of security lanes, efficient TSAPre, and the traffic through the gates tends to be low enough that you usually get through in 5.minutes or less (way less, with TSAPre).

Inside, there really isn't much in the way of amenities - just the usual assortments of Peets, Starbucks, chain restaurants, etc.

That's ok though - the key here is to come in hot (get here with just enough time to make it through the gates, and onto the plane üòÄ< /review>

Lots of money spent, but...

I first flew out of the old terminal at the South end on a turbo prop long thin plane with tight 1-1 or 2-2 seating. 1950s flying to LA to see GPs. The Attendant could barely walk down the aisle not being a midget.

In the 80s the East side southern white terminal had very long walks. That bldg is now replaced. We "lost" several 70# boxes of Alaska sockeye salmon and huge halibut we caught flying back from Yakutat, Anchorage, and SeaTac on the same fumbling unfriendly airline; we applied for a check for full retail at famous sj fish store and finally got it. Same "award" unmentionable airline told us bear spray in our checked bags for 30yd Griz on Situk River was "ok" 3 times, then confiscated $35 REI big canister and holster at the gate!

A couple years ago I flew out of the East side northern terminal, parking in the too small new garage. The airline to Hawaii at the end of the terminal told me to be there "2 and 1/2 hours before the flight" which I did. 3 years in a row. The gate agents weren't there yet for another hour! There is/was totally inadequate seating, telling me it was "designed" to make us stand and wait, with luggage.  Went outside!, It was much faster to check my bag at the curb than the counter. I was sent to the "fast security line" but directed into the long slow security line by a low skill guard. Lots of low skill workers. Only 1 restaurant had a tasty breakfast. On the drab white walls 5hr flight the attendants mostly hid in the back galley and kept us in our seats with bumpy air the whole 5hr flight! When I came back the pick up curb on the other side is too short and too crowded, by design.

And so it goes, stumbling and fumbling, at SJC.

<username>Paulina Lei</username><Review>San Jose airport is not bad. Overall, it is a well-organized airport. Check-ins are usually fast. During popular times of travel, it can be a little busy, but it's a lot better than other airports in terms of handling the large amount of traffic.

The structural design of the airport is a little flawed. If you have a gate that is a small number like 1-9, you have to walk the entire length of the airport to get to your gate. But, can't really complain about this since this is the design.

Most of the time, it is rather clean. However, I have been there a few times and looked under the seats and found some trash.

Restaurants there are quite nice, too. Of course, the airport prices aren't cheap.<//Review></record>

< UserId.>
106206511677592870990<//UserId.>
< username>
Steff A.<//username>
<time>1565679283085< /time><Rate>4</Rate>< text>
I've only flown in and out of this airport once..and I am a fan..

The airport is big enough so there's plenty of room for numerous gates for enough flights in and out of San Jose.  However, it's not so big where gates are separated by buildings and you have to get there by a railed tram or long walks.  The tall glass ceilings allow light to naturally come in and make for an attractive airport.

There's pretty good dining options lined up at Mineta should you need to grab a bite.  The TSA Pre-check line is efficient and gets you through quickly.  They had two Pre-check stations operating when I went through at 7 PM.  There's a cool rotating airplane influenced art piece right outside the security check.  It's a social media moment for sure.

This is the best airport to rent a car from.  The rental car area is literally across the street.  After less than a 10 minute walk, you're in the rental car building lobby.  Fantastic.

Overall, Mineta San Jose Airport is a well designed medium sized airport.  I don't fly here often, but I would have no issues flying to Mineta when need be.  Safe Travels!</text>

<text>Not the most scenic or attractive airport but some friendly people helped us at each desk we interacted with.< /text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOquflw5bo3mTL25P0VSgQyhKMerXbWQouauUrX=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures><user_id>109148558281438214035<//user_id></record></dataset><record>

< username>
Sean Miller</username>
< date>
1575353762454< /date>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Text>
This airport does its job and it does it well. It's much easier and less stressful to navigate than SFO. There are ample food options past security. From arriving at the airport to reaching the gate must have taken around 25-30 minutes max on a lazy Thursday morning.

The only somewhat annoying thing about SJC is that it's not particularly easy to get to from the rest of the Bay Area via public transit - you have to take the Caltrain to San Jose Diridon station and then either take a city bus or take the VTA light rail - not bad, but not great either. But if you are ok with either struggling through public transit or taking an Uber/taxi, then this may just be the best airport in the Bay area.<//Text>

0x808fcbc3fab3c59b:0xbcfa443f6df67e3e< /gmap_id>
<review>Access to this airport is pretty simple from major freeways (101, 87, 17/880). Plenty of short/long term parking. While other airport options exist nearby (SF, Oakland, Monterey) I prefer SJC.
- I predominately travel using American Airlines who has an Admirals Club here and reasonable flight schedule options (although it was better years ago when  SJC was an American hub location). Inside the secured area (where the Gates are, thru TSA) there are plenty of small shops, places for food, both a Peets and $tarBucks coffee, book stores and restrooms.
- I've never had an issue where arriving at least 3 hours before your flight was required (although I did get burned once on a codeshare American flight serviced by Alaskan Airlines who refused me a boarding pass because their self-serve machines were down and waiting in line I got to their ticket counter only 40 minutes before flight time, so I had to schlep my bags back over to the Ametican terminal where they confirmed that if it had been at an American Gate that they would have issued me a boarding pass as long as the Jetbridge door for that flight was still open (and they apologized for their "partner's" overly aggressive rule). American then re-routed my itinerary for free putting me on different/alternate American flights (ones that would have been more expensive if I had booked them) that got me where I was going on-time and gave me upgraded preferred seats - again for free, AND they were done BEFORE my original flight departed (in other words in less than what was left of those 40 minutes even including the inter-terminal foot travel excursion).
- Bottomline is ANYtime there has been any unplanned travel complication (like, equipment/weather canceled flights) American has always taken care of me (arranging ground transportation to a nearby quality hotel, providing dinner vouchers, re-booking onto first thing next morning direct flight to my original location in upgraded seating - all at $0 to me). SJC continues to be my preferred home base.<//review>< Name>
Jayson Jenson< /Name>

<text>The facilities are modern with bathrooms spaced evenly along the concourse. Good variety of restaurants. However, due to airport real estate, the terminal is very linear. That is, all the gates are spread out in a line. The parking, car rental, arrivals and departures for domestic flights are all located across from gate 26. If you land at gate 17 or lower number, you have to walk quite a distance to get to the exit.

There is only one security checkpoint in Terminal B.  Clear, TSA Pre check, and general have separate lines, but all are still funneled through the one area (maybe 5 x-ray lines total of all are open, one or two dedicated to Clear/TSA Pre). This wait can be long for security, depending on the day/time. Note: I have not been in Terminal A (international).< /text></record></dataset><record>

<Text>I love flying in an out of SJC. There is rarely any lines at security to the point where it's faster to go in the regular line than the pre-check line. Because it's still relatively small geographically speaking, you can get from curbside to the gate in less than 20 minutes if you aren't checking a bag. The lines to check bags are also practically non-existent across multiple airlines (american, United, JetBlue, etc), so even if you have to go that route, it won't add too much time. There aren't many food options inside or outside of security so I'd recommend eating before you arrive. However they have a few decent bars so come thirsty.<//Text>< Date>

<resp>None<//resp>< review>
Small. No 1st class check-in line. Priority check-in had 1 person at counter and a line of 5 when we got there. They want you to use the kiosks and bag drop instead.

No recharge stations we could find in domestic terminal. Very few places to plug something in.

No AA or United Club. The Club is a for profit club that wont honor your club memberships. They appear to cater to foreigners flying foreign flag airlines. That and Priority Pass/Diners Club. That's a joke. So prepare to sit at the gate or spend money.

Very limited shopping or dining options.

Unless you hate SFO you are much better off using it.</review>

< text>
SJC may not seem like the fanciest, most accommodating-to-all (or whatever) airport - but it gets it right in core areas. Personally, even living in SF I prefer flying out of this airport. Always ease of access (depart/arrival lanes) and security is very efficient. Rarely wait in long lines or for very long through security, while the process seemed to remain very effective. Always make my flight, easily get home without long baggage claim waits. Lots of stores fulfilling a surprising number of needs inside and easily found without twists or turns or shuttles. Often times I will step out from security and be nearby my gate within just a few minutes. Seems to me this stuff is really what matters in an airport.<//text>

<Gmap_id>0x808fcbc3fab3c59b:0xbcfa443f6df67e3e</Gmap_id><Resp>None< /Resp>< Text>
This airport is tucked away in San Jose and is pretty nice. Due to its location in Silicon Valley there are plenty of tech savey travellers and the bells and whistles to go with them. The loading and unloading zone is fairly busy and could use expansion but other than that everything feels easy going and smooth. The building Is modelled after an airplane hanger and is laid out as a long line with gates laid out along one side. This was wisely done so that travel between terminals is fast. If you have this airport as a choice I would recommend it over many others.< /Text>

<review>I love the silicon valley airport. Easy in and out.

Parking is abundant.  Lot 1 is closed due to renovations. However, the long term lots near Southwest airline is open and price dropped to $18 per day.

Lot's of restaurants, cocktail, beer and coffee options available in the terminals.

Wait times in lines going through security are very fast, with wait times less than 10 minutes.

A layover of 3+ hours allows me to travel down the street (10 minutes) to grab a bite. I may also travel 15 minutes into downtown to walk or grab a quick bite.

Longer layovers can travel to the Westfield Valley Fair shopping center and to the famous Santana Row - (5 miles) 10 minutes drive or by Uber/Lyft.  Great place to shop, eat and walk for an hour.

Great airport.</review>< resp>
None< /resp>

<name>John H.</name><date>1434727995391< /date><Rating>4< /Rating><Review>In terms of location, it's convenient to really anywhere in the SF/Peninsula/OAK/East Bay/SJ South Bay/Silicon Valley/Santa Cruz. This is partially because most of the time you can get through this airport fairly quickly compared to other airports. The city not investing in a people mover (or two) is utterly ridiculous and does a disservice to the city, Silicon Valley, and everyone who utilizes this supposedly high tech airport. So be prepared (possibly) for long terminal walks (exercise). Food and shopping selections are not great. I agree that the roadways/signage are ridiculous and poorly designed. It's nice that the terminals are new/updated, but there are some negatives (I won't get into with that). Public transportation to the airport is substandard. San Jose should do what Oakland is doing and at the least have an actual Light Rail (if not BART) connector train (spur line such as Ohlone/ Almaden) down Airport Parkway/Brokaw from First Street. First Street is fairly close to the airport, and so I can't imagine it would be that expensive ($120 Million or so?) Public transportation though doesn't generate parking revenue for the city you see. The one reason I like this airport, is that usually, it is low stress and efficient compared to most other airports. So getting from point A to Point B is usually relatively easy and hassle free. 3.5 Stars.<//Review>< Pics>
None</Pics>

I also love how the Southwest terminal has a great Jamba Juice bar!  I just wish there were more selections for food in each of the locations.

Out on the sidewalk with no signs providing directions?  We will think twice about flying through this airport again.< /Text>

<rate>5<//rate><review>What's not love? Beautiful architecture, comfortable seating, friendly-knowledgeable staff and for an international airport, small. Even the long lines at TSA are short. This is the center of the digital world.  (Google, Apple and just about every other digital company is nearby.)  Almost every oversized chair is equipped with a power station. < text>
International immigrations on a weekend (9/30/17) is terrible. Only 4 agents (initially 2) for a hundrends of passengers. With Mobile Passport it took us 45m+ to get through. <Rating>3</Rating>< Text>
Airport is dated, and not high tech. Had higher expectations for my first visit to Silicon Valley. . I was given a paper map by a nice rental car lady who said her computer was so slow, and remarked - is that not funny - for being in the high tech capital of the world:) The ATT data service was so overloaded and I had to pull 3 miles away from airport to get a signal for my GPS app. The people at the Airport were very friendly, and I sure was glad to have the paper map as backup if needed :) Also I wanted to buy a kneck pillow for my return flight, but the cheapest one at every single store was 40 Bucks! I expected them to be higher, but that tops anything I have ever seen! They have desk in the gate area, with outlets which is nice. Also there are outlets in a few chairs, which is also helpful. Signage is excellent, which makes it easy to find where to go.< /Text>

<Text>This airport was great until I had to leave the parking lot. Apparently you need a debit/credit card to leave the parking lot!!! It is suppose to be convenient for patrons not just patrons with plastic!!!!  Anyway I had to back up out of the stall, pull to the side and emergency park. Jump out, find a door into airport then look for a kiosk machine (they take cash, wth?) get my ticket, run back to my car before someone hit it, pay and get out of there. 104200568677644151902< /user_id>
<date>1406671484448</date><text>This recently renovated airport is convenient for Bay Area travellers,  especially those who live in the South Bay. It is easy to get in and out of the airport with security lines that often move rather quickly. The staff is friendly most of the time. Unlike most airports (both domestic and international) I've been to, the restroom stalls for women are quite spacious with several hooks and shelves to place belongings; they are also very clean.

The restaurant choices are quite good for an airport of this size, with an emphasis on local eateries and shops. CJ Olson Cherries is a good place to stop by for gifts and snacks while Joe's offers good pizzas.

There's also a free shuttle (Bus 10) that takes passengers to and from SJC, Santa Clara Caltrain and Metro Light Rail Station every 15-30 minutes from 5 am to 11:30pm, daily.</text><Pictures>None</Pictures></record>

< Review>
If you want to have lunch or a cocktail with your friends or family before your flight then choose another airport. The terminals are designed to accommodate passengers only. < text>
This is the perfect Airport to fly in/out Silicon Valley. It's a human sized airport with very nice staff. Very well serviced by public transportation. The lines are reasonably short, you got Free Wifi (Welcome to Silicon Valley). There are pretty descent places to eat and drink. Aircrafts takeoff right after leaving the gate, without taxiing forever, same for landing. Baggage comes very quickly as well ! Most importantly, their Airport is kept clean and bathrooms are always clean too. Having moved to the US in the past years where I was disappointed with poor, dirty, unfriendly airport, SJC just stands out and is definitely to the highest standards I used to in Europe and Asia. Keep on the good work !</text>

<Text>This is my preferred airport, and is much more accessible for South Bay'ers than either SFO or OAK.  I fly here several times per year.  The terminals are accessible, and I don't usually have to wait long for pickup or dropoff.  I have seen security harass Uber drivers, so be discreet when getting a ride.

The security line isn't too long (generally), but plan at least 20 minutes in line just in case.  The long corridor would really benefit from some moving walkways.  But in all, pretty serviceable.< /Text>< pics>

Adam Lasnik</name>
< Text>
This is a medium sized airport that's, overall, a lot more pleasant and efficient than SFO.

- A moderate number of food choices.
- The "Lounge at SJC" is pretty nice; not very crowded, and featuring some tasty light bites for lunch and complimentary drinks at the bar.
- Since the airport isn't too huge, you can typically get to your gate in 10 minutes or less from anywhere in your terminal.
- And since fog is rare here in SJ, your plane is much less likely to be delayed due to weather (coming or going) with SJC vs. SFO.< /Text>

<gmap_id>0x808fcbc3fab3c59b:0xbcfa443f6df67e3e</gmap_id><Review>A real 21st Century airport! I travel all over the world and this just might be my favorite of all. Why? Let me list the reasons:
1. Security took just 5 minutes. I even used passbook on my iPhone with no problem.
2. Free high speed WiFi - I actually watched a couple of You Tube videos and FaceTimed my wife with no lag.
3. Power outlets at EVERY seat! I've been to many other airports where business folks are clustered around the few power outlets hoping to charge up their phones. No problems at SJC!
4. A decent coffee shop (Peets) that isn't Starbucks. Don't get me wrong, they have Starbucks too and it's fine, but I prefer other coffee shops.
5. Car rental across the street. With a passion, I hate arriving at an airport (usually late) and then having to go on a 20 minute bus ride to the rental car center. On the return trip it makes it even worse if you're running late. Why do airports do that? BWI and Denver have ridiculous long bus rides to/from the rental car center. Stupid and inconvenient. SJC, no problem to walk across the street!

All round, a great picture of what a modern airport should be.<//Review><name>Andrew Shaw</name><time>1424466072538<//time>< Response>

<userid>113348736951055038973<//userid>< user_name>
Thomas Devaux< /user_name>
<time>1395529051727< /time>< rate>
5</rate>
<text>This is what an airport should be.

I've travelled a lot and I have to say it's one of my favorites.
It's a bit weird to review an airport since it's rarely a place you deliberately chose. But with the proximity of SFO, it can actually be the case.

First of all, it's brand new. From Parking lot to Gates and Rental Car offices, it feels like it was opened yesterday. It also means it's modern in the way it was conceived.

It's quite small. Compared to SFO, you can walk from A to B without having to rush. You can park for 1h right next to the Arrivals if you have to pick someone, it will just cost you $2 or $4.

It's Silicon Valley! They offer free WiFi. All seats in the waiting area have power and USB plugs. Very appreciable. Parkings has NFC payment (great to show off Google Wallet to visiting family!).

These are all good reasons, but the best is it's never crowded. It's much smaller than SFO, so usually it's easy to park and walk. If you're coming to the Bay Area, and not San Francisco itself, you'll find it more convenient.</text>< pics>
None</pics>

None<//Resp>

< Name>
fraulein casigan< /Name>
<time>1395992068505< /time>< rating>
4<//rating>
< Text>
Flying in and out of SJC is less of a hassle compared to larger airports such as LAX, SFO, LAS, etc. In a nutshell, this airport needed a major uplift. Thanks to SJ for investing plenty of renovations, it looks absolutely nicer! I LOVE the new Terminal B!! Parking garage is larger, more vroom, vroom, vroom for cars to drive, pick up and drop off passengers for/from flights!!

TSA exceeded my expectations! If you do an early bird check in aka Southwest, AA, etc. You can just drop your luggage off quickly with the attendants and easily go through security lines that don't snake throughout the terminal area. You have enough time to enjoy hanging out at the airport's restaurants, mini bars, and shops.

Although, not much shopping here unless you consider stopping at The Hudson for a small read of their magazines. However, Peet's would be a good choice if you're still groggy for a morning flight. Grab a nice cup of coffee or tea! Unless you're off to Vegas or Miami, maybe a cocktail or beer at The Brit, while watching the news or sports while waiting for your flight, can make the time go by a lot quicker before partying it up in style!

Did I mention, they offer FREE WiFi? Yes! Of course, we're in the heart of Silicon Valley. Many tech companies in the Bay Area. For those who are always busy with work and on the go, don't fret my friends. While waiting for your flight, you can sit down with your laptop and plug it into a power outlet on the side of your seat!! How cool is that?!

Downside to SJC...ticket prices to fly in/out from here is a little bit steep as opposed to SFO or OAK but the extra dollars is worth the trip! Happy travels!</Text>

< Text>
This is a model of a "perfect" airport.

Operational reasons:
Best on-time performance ranking in California.
Weather-delays are exceedingly rare - only 5 days per year.
Not overwhelmingly-busy like SFO.
Good highway/road traffic management.
Somewhat fast TSA lines.

--Amenities--:
Free & Fast WiFi.
Free ground transportation to VTA/Caltrain.
Power outlets in gate areas.
Clean and modern seating areas and bathrooms.

The best domestic carriers:
Virgin, Southwest, Jet Blue. Yay.

Negatives:
All parking (even the "economy lot") can be expensive. $20/day minimum.
Terminal B is nearly a half-mile long (!). That's about a 10 minute walk from end-to-end.< /Text>

< review>
(Translated by Google) Since it is not a large airport, the waiting time for each work is relatively short and it goes smoothly overall. There is also a little shopping space at the airport.
International flights are basically Terminal A and domestic flights are Terminal B, but in some cases domestic flights may leave from Terminal A, so it is recommended to check in advance. That was the case before when I went to New York on United Air.
When my parents came to California, I took a direct flight from this airport to Japan. Actually, flights from Japan to San Francisco are cheaper at tens of thousands of yen, but my parents do not have much experience traveling abroad, so I dared to choose a direct flight to this airport so as not to get lost in the airport. My parents also said it wasn't difficult to arrive.
You can rest assured that someone will manage the belt lane when your luggage arrives. The lanes at this airport are short and can quickly fill up with luggage. I was worried that the bag wouldn't break.

<review>(Translated by Google) ANA's check-in counter opens 3 hours before departure. The same applies to the luggage deposit counter. If you want to get in the airport earlier than this, you can do "online check-in" with "only carry-on luggage". You can use "The Club at SJC" with Priority Pass (as of May 2018). In front of Gate 15, often very close to the departure gate for ANA flights. It is about 15 minutes by car from San Jose city, so it is quite close. Baggage inspection takes a considerable amount of time. When crowded, it's better to wait for an hour just in case. By the way (although there are no ANA customers alone), it is quite vacant because the peak is exceeded early in the morning 3 hours before the departure of ANA flight.
